-- Stocks in South Africa Fall For Second Day, Led by Northam Platinum, Sasol
-- B y   N i c k y   S m i t h
-- 2010-09-23T10:53:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-23/south-african-stocks-fall-for-second-day-anglo-american-anglogold-active.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  retreated for a second day, dropping 92.26, or 0.3
percent, to 28,630.46 at 12:05 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ), Africa’s largest producer
of the metal, rose 3.52 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 322.20 rand.
Gold traded near a record as the dollar weakened on prospects
for a further easing of monetary policy by the U.S. central
bank, boosting prices of commodities priced in the currency.  Harmony Gold Mining Ltd.  (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-biggest
producer of the metal, rose 1.42 rand, or 1.8 percent, to 80.31
rand, headed for the highest close in almost a week.  Combined Motor Holdings Ltd.  (CMH SJ), a South African car
retailer, increased 40 cents, or 3.4 percent, to 12.20 rand, the
highest intraday level since Feb. 11, 2008, after saying
earnings for the first half through August will rise as much as
140 percent from a year earlier.  Northam Platinum Ltd.  (NHM SJ), the miner of the metal fell
66 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 44.84 rand. The operator of the
deepest platinum mine was reduced to “sell” from “buy” by
Investec Ltd.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL SJ), the largest producer of automotive
fuel from coal, retreated for a third day, slipping 1.01 rand,
or 0.3 percent, to 304.50 rand. Oil fell as much as 1.1 percent
to $73.89 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Nicky Smith  in Johannesburg at 
